item.title: Test CSI plugin liveness probe
item.description:
Related discussion

https://github.com/longhorn/longhorn/issues/3907

Test CSI plugin liveness probe should recover CSI socket file

Given healthy Longhorn cluster

When delete the Longhorn CSI socket file on one of the node(node-1). rm /var/lib/kubelet/plugins/driver.longhorn.io/csi.sock

Then the longhorn-csi-plugin-* pod on node-1 should be restarted.

And the csi-provisioner-* pod on node-1 should be restarted.
And the csi-resizer-* pod on node-1 should be restarted.
And the csi-snapshotter-* pod on node-1 should be restarted.
And the csi-attacher-* pod on node-1 should be restarted.

item.title: Test filesystem trim
item.description:
Related issue

https://github.com/longhorn/longhorn/issues/836

Case 1: Test filesystem trim during writing

Given A 10G volume created.

And Volume attached to node-1.

And Make a filesystem like EXT4 or XFS for the volume.

And Mount the filesystem on a mount point.

Then Run the below shell script with the correct mount point specified:

#!/usr/bin/env bash

MOUNT_POINT=${1}

dd if=/dev/urandom of=/mnt/data bs=1M count=8000
sync
CKSUM=`md5sum /mnt/data | awk '{print $1}'`

for INDEX in {1..10..1};
do
  rm -rf ${MOUNT_POINT}/data

  dd if=/mnt/data of=${MOUNT_POINT}/data &

  RAND_SLEEP_INTERVAL=$(($(($RANDOM%50))+10))
  sleep ${RAND_SLEEP_INTERVAL}

  fstrim ${MOUNT_POINT}
  while [ `ps aux | grep "dd if" | grep -v grep | wc -l` -eq "1" ]
  do
    sleep 1
  done

  CUR_CKSUM=`md5sum ${MOUNT_POINT}/data | awk '{print $1}'`
  if [ $CUR_CKSUM != $CKSUM ]
  then
    echo "invalid file found, expected checksum $CKSUM, current checksum $CUR_CKSUM"
    exit 1
  fi

  rm -f ${MOUNT_POINT}/data
done

Then The script execution should succeed.

item.title: Test Longhorn system backup should sync from the remote backup target
item.description:
Steps

Given Custom resource SystemBackup (foo) exist in AWS S3,

And System backup (foo) downloaded from AWS S3.

And Custom resource SystemBackup (foo) deleted.

When Upload the system backup (foo) to AWS S3.

And Create a new custom resource SystemBackup(foo).

This needs to be done before the system backup gets synced to the cluster.

Then Should see the synced messages in the custom resource SystemBackup(foo).

item.title: Test upgrade for migrated Longhorn on Rancher
item.description:
Related discussion

https://github.com/longhorn/longhorn/discussions/4198

Context: since few customers used our broken chart longhorn 100.2.1+up1.3.1 on Rancher (Now fixed) with the workaround. We would like to verify the future upgrade path for those customers.

Steps

  1. Set up a cluster of Kubernetes 1.20.
  2. Adding this repo to the apps section in new rancher UI
    1. repo: https://github.com/PhanLe1010/charts.git
    2. branch: release-v2.6-longhorn-1.3.1.
  3. Access old rancher UI by navigating to <your-rancher-url>/g.
  4. Install Longhorn 1.0.2.
  5. Create/attach some volumes. Create a few recurring snapshot/backup job that run every minutes.
  6. Upgrade Longhorn to v1.2.4.
  7. Migrate Longhorn to new chart in new rancher UI https://longhorn.io/kb/how-to-migrate-longhorn-chart-installed-in-old-rancher-ui-to-the-chart-in-new-rancher-ui/.
  8. Upgrade to longhorn 100.2.1+up1.3.1 in the UI.
  9. Verify the upgrade would be stuck at with error:
  10. Apply the workaround
  11. Retry upgrade to longhorn 100.2.1+up1.3.1 in the UI.
  12. Verify the upgrade is ok.
  13. Verify that the user can successfully upgrade to future chart releases (e.g., Longhorn v1.3.2) from this version longhorn 100.2.1+up1.3.1.
